d E natan Luum
Antwerp 5 sber 1681
Dublin
according as I wrott to you on the 26: hast have send to rotd to
m. Francus greene wood the 2 packette of laces provided by yd order of
thich inclosed you have the invoyce, which finding wright pleaseto
pass to my credit, & make mee debtor for as much & have drowne
this day on m. George cole £ 148„9 „5 sterlinx att 35 s is £259„16:6
att 3 a 4 dayes, sicht, not doubting bust that you have given hun order
to accept my bill: god send the laies sufe to ft yd. hand, & I do not
quession, butt you will finde not onely content: butt incorridg ment
to in order much more towaids winser assuring you of my endeavour
to serve you ou all respects, nith theusmost of my power: I have
sent no Antwarp laces because that sort proves ordinaire deaver then
thers, which is the needfull aft present from
5 ditto
London dmond warner
S in answer to yd of 15 past as for the croor om the packest N24
Sfinde yd autt: is debtor bast for £185:17:6, so that ift is a mistale
in drawinge of itt out: as for the conetts in last packest, they ane vere
neare to yd patt: which made mee send them, butt for them wish you
what you can not sell returne, though itt shoud ee a month or 2 henu
there is alwayes opportunitie att london for bruges by long sea, bett itt
bemadeup closely, to deliver to my order & then Ilee dake care att
bruges: gonu complaine of the lace trade, alwayes, this time, a yeare
is the last demand for ncost people beeng in the countray, which will
amend saddamly for vee observe alwayes dhemost demand to wards
sommer & to wards inter I could with last packet was gott safe
to you & sam sure you will finde content & as well bought, if not
bester then any shallbe able to do, haveing taken my time to the pimpost
so pray compare them to thers, & lest mee have yd opinion as for
the remaining stolen laces, wee find, so much opontion by the officers,
that I doubt vee shall make bast a badd acctt. of itt, the governor
did last promiseto in forme him self att gant aboutt & gve
us satisfaction in the meane, while wee cere continually riffled of,
'intend to be att brussels inthin 2 dayes & what hopes there remaiynes
for you, may be confident if it had been my owne I coud have
don no more: returne you my thankes for accepting my bill, & nitt
offers off my servie remaine
5 ditto
London george cole
S my last to you, was ou the 29:t past, sence read yd 2„ f ditto, sam
forry that you have drawne on mee, & coud have wighed you had
expected my advise, whower seeng tis so shall punctually descharge yd
bill for the acctt., as itt is drawne, I have this daye drawne on you
one houndred and fointie cight pourd 9 ƒ 5 pence starling att
shree off four doips socht payable to the order off no henry maynard
for my owne valeu and for actt off t Elnatan lamon off dublin which
please to pay accordingly, nou ast for the concernes of I:8. deseased
inclosed send you a proieit accordingly to which you & the other enecusoins
pleasito send mee a dischange made by asworne notary p send mee, the
balance of that acctt was £180:18:1 according to the copie sent you,
& outre fiest of april have send you the inroyce off to on heads ofe lo -
verselde bought for yd acctt ams to £183:16:9 oft which I finde
I then desired you to make up the ballance of said owians acctt, so that
there shall be ducto mee £2:18: 8 fle mush which will be formid some
there eles as alsoo the £34:10 you doew last att 35: 3, non for what
you make mee debt, upon mj autt of said rivian, there is so many
abatements, allowed in clearing the acctt, & port of letters & that
I beleave I shall come short, whoever shall send a note there of
whilst in the meane while pray faile not to send mee a discharge
as need fall if any difference thars ian alwayes be advissed never theleis
seeng you have more then the valeu in yd handes recommend yd panctu=
allitie in al & remaine
ondon henry maynard
Antwerp adij 5 sber 1682
& my last to you was on the 29t past to which referre, onely once
more recommendruy yd endeavour s'expedition to the northrens then
desire non have before mee yd of 18 & 21 ditto the cloather sold aff £42
are the 6N salver march: butt please to observe that I mast yett them
drest p ued which cost about £10- sremish a pr. which is brought to
the aust of chargies so that parcell is wel, als also one before of the
2 p I have geven you credit for my ½ share in the goods schipped as
for the kersie cotton & swanships bayes lett them rest hhe finther
order js till fort £200- for yd att aust shall find due complyance
Iam vere sens cole tobe so back ward that, I can not prevent yd
drawing, because Ihate that before all things in the wored, p yett
mony doth come in as I could have expeat id, intending p next
to send you a note of what is ytt standing out upon our autt till
xber last, that you might sea the reason oft itt in the meare while
if S can serve you with 2 a £300- in geld Ib le send itt presenly
feryd acctt have my noless by mee att present whuch Ican not vere
wel sill as itt cost mee, except & stay for the turne vil dacetes
att ƒ5- pastols att ƒ9- souveraines att ƒ15- nithe parell beeg
swetall Jacobus p cavolus as to what you say, oft paying goods
I knous all vere will, & was Iable to do itt I shoad saffer no boditto
draw en mee att time batt haveny mony ready, bust itt is nott so yct
so must have patence though I beyge of you to beas favo favourabe
an posibly you can whilst inclosed you have £148:9:5 att 3 a 4
sicht on m george cole in my owne bill, for which pray procure
theneed full & pass to my acctt if you order the gold yd will besome
cleared I sall want att least 10 p 6N silver marchx more before gber
s am fory klack tarries so long, heamy not oneword off frews from
hun, god sond hun wel, you have schped, & good prveell ne han
